For each selected architectural tier, one set of PRSM(+T) plus DM exists.

- Governance & Security

For each tier, the intermediate results are available. Intermediate PRSM(+T) models and DM are results of one Process Pipeline iteration.

The final results are highlighted by the "FINAL_" prefix and are the results used by the manuscript.

Tier. Governance & Security

Principle. “Always authenticate data flows and information requested by internal and external users.”

Rationale.


The PCS implementation consists of multiple different components which needs specific authentication and authorization capabilities.

By following the need-to-know principle, user access controls and authorisation procedures can be enforced. Its objective is to ensure that only authorised individuals gain access to information or systems necessary to undertake their duties.

Integrity.
PCS system always authenticate flows and information requested by internal and external stakeholders.

Confidentiality.
PCS system ensures that data are accessible only to those authorized to have access.

Economic Risk Mitigation.
By authenticating all flows and information, the risk of cyber attacks will be mitigated. Hence, the potential risk of financial loss is mitigated as well;

• Usefulness.
The PCS stakeholders consider the PCS solution as useful and are motivated with its implementation

• Data Privacy.
 Personal data of all internal and external PCS users are transmitted encrypted and only accessible to those who have the permissions to the personal data.

Health & Safety Risk Mitigation.
If the PCS data are available and reliable, the system mitigates the potential risk to people in the intended contexts of use. (e.g., explosive content in the cargo process)

• DAI3 - Data & AI Governance
GDPR and ethical compliancy on par with legal requirements

Principle. “SaaS goes above PaaS; PaaS goes above IaaS; IaaS goes above On-Premise.”

Tier. PCS Messaging Portal

Principle. “SaaS goes above PaaS; PaaS goes above IaaS; IaaS goes above On-Premise.”

Rationale.


SaaS solutions help to reduce the cost and maintenance overhead of running cloud services.

The technical knowledge does not need to be at company level and can be pass to the provider. This minimizes the risk of incidents.

It is necessary to ensure that the cloud solution comply with the company infrastructure and can be integrated.

Fault tolerance.
Even in case of software or hardware faults on the provider side, the SaaS solution would/should operate as usual. If, and only if the SaaS solution would have a hardware or software error, “the system would perform under acceptable and predictable bounds”. Due to the Business Impact Analysis, Business Continuity is an important attribute for PCS.
Scalability.
SaaS solutions should always be scalable. For the PCS solution, a message volume of 10,000 messages was calculated. Over the years, the volume of messages will increase by a factor of 10. Therefore, SaaS solutions must be scalable by design.

Serviceability.
The Life Cycle Management (LCM) for SaaS solutions is handled by the provider, hence, less support employees are necessary.

Availability.
If the system is not available, the users and 
customers do not trust and do not use the solution.

Reusability.
SaaS solutions can be reused by more than one system, even over customers and can be part of other solutions. Resources at the provider side can be shared.

Tier. PCS Market Portal

Principle. "Use the Airport Service Bus (ASB) for sharing / exchanging of operational data between applications and parties where routing, filtering, data transformation (integration rules) or transport transformation capabilities are needed."

Rationale.

The ASB is an integration platform, because it adds functionalities to integrate two or more known systems. 

ASB adds functionality like routing, transformation, aggregation, throttling, basic reliable messaging and user management.

Beyond, the ASB causes more integration work. This need is due to the increased data exchange when the # of connected applications increases.

Solid Foundation - Connectivity
[Custom]  system performance grows with adding more resources

XXXXX Availability. 
The ASB is operational and accessible when the PCS solution needs it. If not, it could cause delays in the Cargo process and hence, flight delays could be the result and cause more environmental impacts.

Tier. PCS Market Portal

Principle. "Use the Airport Service Bus (ASB) for sharing / exchanging of operational data between applications and parties where routing, filtering, data transformation (integration rules) or transport transformation capabilities are needed."

Rationale.

The ASB is an integration platform, because it adds functionalities to integrate two or more known systems. 

ASB adds functionality like routing, transformation, aggregation, throttling, basic reliable messaging and user management.

Beyond, the ASB causes more integration work. This need is due to the increased data exchange when the # of connected applications increases.

Time behaviour.
The PCS integration / connection to the ASB does not affect the response, processing times and throughput rates of other systems and meets the PCS requirements.

Modularity.
The ASB is responsible to act as an additional layer to de-couple the external systems from the core system. The ASB is in-between and takes care of the translation. Changes at external systems does not affect the core - and the other way around.

Scalability.
The ASB (2.0) has the ability to scale and can be used across PCS boundaries. By using the ASB for a variety of systems without implementing a new scalability mechanism, costs are mitigated.

Interoperability.
By using the ASB for the PCS solution, information can be received and exchanged with other systems and other users beyond the internal and external stakeholders.

Tier. PCS Core and Architecture

Principle. "The system is made of loosely coupled components."

Rationale.

There are many different types of communication protocols currently supported to deliver Cargo related messages or request Cargo related information by customers. To be able to handle all kinds communication, loosely coupled components are necessary. 

E.g., the PCS Core System is implemented in Sub-Components and is loosely coupled to the Business Engine which is implemented outside of the Core. In addition, the responsibilties of the components are distributed across different layers and messages (i.e., API) are used for communication between the layers.
